8. Refactoring Approach and Benefits
Approach Taken
1.	Read through the function and identified 10 distinct responsibilities from comments and code blocks
2.	Extracted each responsibility into a separate, clearly named function
3.	Replaced two conditional chains (output_format and report_type) with the Strategy pattern using dictionaries
4.	Refactored the main function to simply coordinate calls to helper functions in sequence
5.	Verified behavior preservation by running the existing test suite

Benefits Gained
•	Each function can be tested independently — validate_report_params can be tested without needing real sales data
•	Main function reads like a table of contents — easy to understand the overall flow at a glance
•	Adding a new output format requires one dictionary entry, not a new elif branch
•	Bug fixes are isolated — fixing date filtering only requires changing filter_by_date_range
•	New developers can understand one small function without holding the entire 180-line function in their head
•	Functions like calculate_basic_metrics could be reused elsewhere in the codebase

Key Learning
Complex functions are rarely doing one job badly — they are usually doing many jobs adequately, hidden inside one giant function. Decomposition does not add new logic, it just gives existing logic better names and homes.

